\begin_layout Section*
ROC Curve and Random Classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Q3.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{t}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined with no regard to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\p_{\D}\left(h_{t}\left(x\right)=1\mid y\right)=\p_{\D}\left(h_{t}\left(x\right)=1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now, since 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{t}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 doesn't take 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 into account, we get that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\p_{\D}\left(h_{t}\left(x\right)=1\right) & =\p_{Z\sim U\left[0,1\right]}\left(Z\ge t\right)\\
 & =t
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we want 
\begin_inset Formula $\tpr\left(x\right)=p$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 must be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
this is terribly wrong.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Q3.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\tpr\left(t\right)=p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From the law of total probability, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\p_{\D}\left(h_{t}\left(x\right)=1\mid y=1\right)\p\left(y=1\right)+\p_{\D}\left(h_{t}\left(x\right)=1\mid y=0\right)\p\left(y=0\right)=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tpr\left(t\right)=p$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\p_{\D}\left(y=1\right)+\p_{\D}\left(y=0\right)=1$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot\p_{\D}\left(y=1\right)+\fpr\left(t\right)\cdot\left(1-\p_{\D}\left(y=1\right)\right)=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From this we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\fpr\left(t\right) & =\frac{1-p\cdot\p_{\D}\left(y=1\right)}{1-\p_{\D}\left(y=1\right)}\\
 & \uneq 1\frac{1}{1-\gamma}-p\cdot\frac{\gamma}{1-\gamma}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1\right]:$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\p_{\D}\left(y=1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
co
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Q4.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recall that the ROC curve can be defined as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tpr$
\end_inset

 as a function of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\fpr$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(p\right)=\frac{1}{1-\gamma}-p\cdot\frac{\gamma}{1-\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function that takes a 
\begin_inset Formula $\tpr$
\end_inset

 and calculates the 
\begin_inset Formula $\fpr$
\end_inset

.
 This is derived from the revious question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since this is a non-increasing linear polynomial of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tpr$
\end_inset

, then it's inverse - a linear polynomial of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\fpr$
\end_inset

, is non-decreasing.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
co
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

